  0. Additional Definitions.

  As used herein, "this License" refers to version 3 of the GNU Lesser
General Public License, and the "GNU GPL" refers to version 3 of the GNU
General Public License.

  "The Library" refers to a covered work governed by this License,
other than an Application or a Combined Work as defined below.

  An "Application" is any work that makes use of an interface provided
by the Library, but which is not otherwise based on the Library.
Defining a subclass of a class defined by the Library is deemed a mode
of using an interface provided by the Library.

  A "Combined Work" is a work produced by combining or linking an
Application with the Library, which is used to convey a work based on
the Library, with the Library being used to provide services to
Application users.

  "Minimal Source Code" for a Combined Work means the source code for
the Application or other Combined Work, and any source code for any
modules that it links with; but, as a special exception, it need not
include source code for modules that are standard libraries of the
Application.

  "Corresponding Source" for a Combined Work means the Corresponding
Source for the Application or other Combined Work, and any source code
for any modules with which the Combined Work is linked to form a
Combined Work in which the Library is used.

  1. Exception to Section 3 of the GNU GPL.

  You may convey a covered work under sections 3 and 4 of this License
without being bound by section 3 of the GNU GPL.

  2. Conveying Modified Versions.

  If you modify a copy of the Library, and, in your modifications, a
facility refers to a function or data to be supplied by an Application
that uses the facility (other than as an argument passed when the
facility is invoked), then you may convey a copy of the modified
version:

   a) under this License, provided that you make the Modified Source
   Code available to the Application under the terms of this License,
   as described in section 3; or

   b) under the GNU GPL, as described in section 3.

  3. Conveying Source Code.

  Each time you convey a Covered Work, the Corresponding Source for the
Covered Work must be made available to the recipients of the Covered
Work under the terms of this License or a special exception.
You must supply the Corresponding Source in a reasonable manner on or
before the date you convey the Covered Work.  If you have already
conveyed the Covered Work under section 2, you must also make the
Corresponding Source available to recipients on or before the date
you convey the Covered Work.

  In addition, you must do one of these things:

    a) Accompany the work with the complete source code for the Library
    including whatever changes were used in the work (which must be
    distributed under Sections 1 and 2 above); and, if the work
    includes an Application, the Corresponding Source for the
    Application as a whole, and any source code for any modules that
    it links with, including any software components or other files
    that are required to be linked to enable linking the Application
    with the Library (the Minimal Source Code for the Application).

    b) Use a suitable shared library mechanism for linking with the
    Library.  A suitable mechanism is one that (1) uses at run time a
    copy of the library already present on the user's computer system,
    rather than copying library functions into the executable, and (2)
    will operate properly with a modified version of the library, if
    the user installs one, as long as the modified version is
    interface-compatible with the version that the work was made with.

    c) Accompany the work with a written offer, valid for at least
    three years and valid for as long as you offer spare parts or
    customer support for that model of the Application, to give anyone
    who possesses the object code either (1) a copy of the Corresponding
    Source for all the software in the work that is covered by this
    License, on a durable physical medium customarily used for software
    interchange, for a price no more than your reasonable cost of
    physically performing this conveying of source, or (2) access to
    copy the Corresponding Source from a network server at no charge.

    d) If you convey the object code by offering access from a
    designated place, offer equivalent access to copy the above
    specified Corresponding Source from the same place.

    e) Verify that the user has already received a copy of the
    Corresponding Source.

  The Corresponding Source need not include anything that users
can regenerate automatically from other parts of the Corresponding
Source.

  4. Combined Works.

  You may convey a Combined Work under this License, or under the GNU
GPL, as described in section 3.  If the Combined Work does not provide
a standard library facility that provides the function or data
supplied by the Application, you must still provide the minimal
facilities and functions required by the Combined Work, and must
ensure that any user of the Combined Work that links to the
Application can use those facilities and functions.

  5. Combined Libraries.

  You may place library facilities that are based on the Library, or
any part thereof, into a single library together with other library
facilities that are not Applications and are not covered by this
License, and convey such a combined library under terms of your
choice, if you do both of the following:

   a) Accompany the combined library with a copy of the same work based
   on the Library, uncombined with any other library facilities,
   conveyed under the terms of this License.

   b) Give prominent notice with the combined library that part of it
   is a work based on the Library, and explaining where to find the
   accompanying uncombined form of the same work.

