           How to Apply These Terms to Your New Libraries

  If you develop a new library, and you want it to be of the greatest
possible use to the public, we recommend making it free software that
everyone can redistribute and change.  You can do so with permission
from the copyright holders.

  However, we want to make sure that a library cannot be incorporated
into proprietary programs.  If we distribute a library as a component
of a program that you write or to which you link a library, we want
to ensure that the user of the program can use that library, and can
understand how to do so.  To protect your rights, we want to prevent
the user of the program that includes the library from being asked
to waive rights to use the library.  To make sure the library is used
by all, we have to make clear that there is no warranty for the free
library.  If the library is distributed as object code or executable
with the source code (or you distribute the library as source code
along with the executable or object code), you must provide the
machine-readable source code as specified in Section 2.  You may
charge a fee for the physical act of transferring a copy, and you may
at your option offer warranty protection in exchange for a fee.  If
the library is distributed as source code, you must make clear that
there is no warranty for the library.  You must also provide
instructions enabling the user to interface the library with the
executable.  If you distribute the library as object code or
executable with the source code not provided, you must provide
source code in the manner specified in Section 2, and you must
distribute such source code with the object code or executable,
as specified in Section 2 of this License.  If you distribute the
object code or executable with the source code embedded in a machine
readable or commonly used printed form, you must provide the source
code in the manner specified in Section 2 and you must provide
instructions that will inform any user how to obtain the source code
from a network server.  This requirement applies to the work as a
whole, and to any and all parts of the work regardless of how they
are packaged.  This requirement does not affect the user's right,
under applicable law, to make alternate arrangements for obtaining
source code.

  If the executable is linked with a library that is not a shared
library or a dynamically linked executable, but a statically linked
executable that includes the library, you must provide the object
code files for the library, plus any source code for any modules that
the executable is linked to use, including any data and/or static
variables used to initialize those modules, that you have not
distributed as source code, in the form of source code files, in
the manner specified in Section 2.  If you link or combine the library
with other modules in a way that creates a combined library that is
a derivative of the library (if the library is linked with the
executable), you must distribute the corresponding source code for
the combined library (which includes the source code for the modules
it contains), along with the object code or executable, under the
terms of Section 2, plus any source code for any modules with which
the executable is linked to form a combined library that is a
derivative of the library.  You must do this regardless of whether
the executable is distributed as a shared library or as a separate
file.  This requirement does not affect any user rights under
applicable law.
